new data structure: std::flat_map, std::flat_set
1. Underlying Structure: It wraps two standalone linear containers. By default, KeyContainer and MappedContainer are both std::vector templates
2. Complexity Performance: Lookups take \(O(\log N)\) time via binary search (std::lower_bound). Insertions and deletions take linear O(N) time because elements must physically shift in the contiguous array
3. Iterator Stability: Unlike std::map, adding or removing items invalidates all iterators and references because underlying vectors may reallocate or shift positions

When to use:
Use std::flat_map when data is built once and queried often, or if the container size remains relatively small (under a few hundred items).
Stick to std::map if your workflow requires continuous, random insertions and deletions across a massive collection.

